06190nam a22011895i 9780691197586DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911975867 a10.1515/97806911975862doi  a(DE-B1597)539897  a(OCoLC)1130906147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a128/.12231 aCottingham, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Search of the Soul :bA Philosophical Essay /cJohn Cottingham. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword and Acknowledgements -- t1. Humanity in Quest of the Soul -- t2. The Evolution of the Soul -- t3. Soul, Science, and Subjectivity -- t4. The Partly Hidden Soul -- t5. The Soul and the Transcendent -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow our beliefs about the soul have developed through the ages, and why an understanding of it still matters todayThe concept of the soul has been a recurring area of inquiry since ancient times. What do we mean when we talk about finding our soul, how do we know we have one, and does it hold any relevance in today's scientifically and technologically dominated society? From Socrates and Darwin to Augustine and Freud, In Search of the Soul takes readers on a concise, accessible journey into the origins of the soul in Western philosophy and culture, and examines how the idea has developed throughout history to the present. Touching on literature, music, art, and theology, John Cottingham illustrates how far from being redundant in contemporary times, the soul attunes us to the importance of meaning and value, experience and growth. A better understanding of the soul might help all of us better understand what it is to be human.Cottingham delves into the evolution of our thoughts about the soul through landmark works-including those of Aristotle, Plato, and Descartes. He considers the nature of consciousness and subjective experience, and discusses the psychoanalytic view that large parts of the human psyche are hidden from direct conscious awareness. He also reflects on the mysterious and universal longing for transcendence that is an indelible part of our human makeup. Exploring the soul's many dimensions-historical, moral, psychological, and spiritual-Cottingham makes a case for how it exerts a powerful force on all of us.In Search of the Soul is a testimony to how the soul remains a profoundly significant aspect of human flourishing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSoul. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aCartesian automata.  aDante.  aFaust.  aKierkegaard.  aLeon Kass.  aPlatonic.  aSickness unto Death.  aSubjectivity.  aT. S. Eliot.  aThe Hungry Soul.  aconsciousness.  aghosts.  ahuman embodiment.  ahuman fulfillment.  ahuman nature.  aimmaterial.  aimmateriality.  aimmortality.  aloss.  ametaphysics.  amortality.  anatural versus supernatural.  anaturalism.  aobjective science.  aobjectivity.  aopacity of the soul.  apanpsychist.  apsyche.  apsychic integration.  aself-fashioning.  asoul-searching.  aspirituality.  ateleology and human destiny.  athe body.  athe shrinking soul.  atranscendent.  atrialism.  ayearning for God.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle 